and cartographic region in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries through their imperial maps. Until then, the region had never been clearly distinguished from “the East” or “the Orient.” In the course of their colonial activities, however, the British began to conceive of the Middle East as a separate and distinct part of the world, with consequences that continue to be felt today. As they reimagined boundaries, the British produced, disputed, and finally dramatically transformed the geography of the area—both culturally and physically—over the course of their colonial era. Using a wide variety of primary texts and historical maps to show how the idea of the Middle East came into being, Dislocating the Orient will interest historians of the Middle East, the British empire, cultural geography, and cartography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCartographyxPolitical aspectszGreat Britain. 0aCartographyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aCartographyzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aMiddle East - Name. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAsian history.  aBritish and Irish history.  aMiddle Eastern history.  aPalestine.  aSyria.  acritical cartography.  acultural historical geography.  ahistorical geography.  ahistory of education.  ahistory of science.  aorientalism.  atheory in the history of cartography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022645133640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226451473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226451473/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles